Your code is valid TypeScript if you're only creating the Map. The problem is usually one of these:

1. Missing closing brackets (your snippet is incomplete)
Make sure you close the object and array:

export interface Product {
  id: number;
  prodGroup: string;
  values: Map<string, any>;
}

export const DEFAULT_PRODUCTS: Product[] = [
  {
    id: 1,
    prodGroup: 'default',
    values: new Map([
      ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
      ['price', 29.99],
      ['category', 'Electronics'],
      ['available', true],
    ]),
  },
];
2. If you're using Angular and displaying Map in a template
Angular templates don't iterate over Map directly with *ngFor. You need the keyvalue pipe:

<div *ngFor="let item of product.values | keyvalue">
  {{ item.key }}: {{ item.value }}
</div>
3. If you're loading this from JSON
Map is not JSON-serializable. If this data comes from an API or a JSON file, use a plain object instead:

export interface Product {
  id: number;
  prodGroup: string;
  values: Record<string, any>;
}

export const DEFAULT_PRODUCTS: Product[] = [
  {
    id: 1,
    prodGroup: 'default',
    values: {
      name: 'Wireless Mouse',
      price: 29.99,
      category: 'Electronics',
      available: true,
    },
  },
];
This is generally the preferred approach unless you specifically need Map features.

4. Avoid any
You can make it safer:

values: Map<string, string | number | boolean>;
or

type ProductValue = string | number | boolean;

values: Map<string, ProductValue>;
