In TypeScript, a two-value tuple is written as [T1, T2].

Array of string/string tuples
const entries: [string, string][] = [
  ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
  ['category', 'Electronics'],
];
Array of string/number tuples
const prices: [string, number][] = [
  ['price', 29.99],
  ['stock', 100],
];
Mixed value types
type Value = string | number | boolean;

const entries: [string, Value][] = [
  ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
  ['price', 29.99],
  ['available', true],
];
Using with Map
type Value = string | number | boolean;

const entries: [string, Value][] = [
  ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
  ['price', 29.99],
  ['available', true],
];

const map = new Map<string, Value>(entries);
Alternatively, you can define a reusable tuple type:

type Entry = [string, string | number | boolean];

const entries: Entry[] = [
  ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
  ['price', 29.99],
  ['available', true],
];
This is the most common pattern when the same tuple type is used in multiple places.


