What you're seeing is Node.js/console's abbreviated output. It collapses nested arrays into [Array].

For example:

const values: [string, string | number | boolean][] = [
  ['name', 'Wireless Mouse'],
  ['price', 29.99],
  ['category', 'Electronics'],
  ['available', true],
];

console.log({ values });
may print:

{
  values: [ [Array], [Array], [Array], [Array] ]
}
To see the full contents
console.log(values);
Output:

[
  [ 'name', 'Wireless Mouse' ],
  [ 'price', 29.99 ],
  [ 'category', 'Electronics' ],
  [ 'available', true ]
]
Or stringify it:

console.log(JSON.stringify(values, null, 2));
Output:

[
  ["name", "Wireless Mouse"],
  ["price", 29.99],
  ["category", "Electronics"],
  ["available", true]
]
If you're logging an object in Node.js, you can also use:

import util from 'node:util';

console.log(util.inspect({ values }, { depth: null }));
or

console.dir({ values }, { depth: null });
If this is Angular/Chrome DevTools
The browser console normally expands arrays automatically. If you're seeing [Array], it's most likely coming from Node.js (console.log/util.inspect) or a test runner like Jest.

