A Record is usually a better fit than Map when your keys are strings and you want JSON-friendly data.

Define a Record
type ProductValue = string | number | boolean;

type ProductValues = Record<string, ProductValue>;
Create a Record
const values: ProductValues = {
  name: 'Wireless Mouse',
  price: 29.99,
  category: 'Electronics',
  available: true,
};
Use it in your interface
interface Product {
  id: number;
  prodGroup: string;
  values: Record<string, string | number | boolean>;
}

const DEFAULT_PRODUCTS: Product[] = [
  {
    id: 1,
    prodGroup: 'default',
    values: {
      name: 'Wireless Mouse',
      price: 29.99,
      category: 'Electronics',
      available: true,
    },
  },
];
Access values
console.log(product.values.name);
console.log(product.values['price']);
Iterate
for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(product.values)) {
  console.log(key, value);
}
Output:

name Wireless Mouse
price 29.99
category Electronics
available true
For most application data (especially if it's stored as JSON or sent over HTTP), Record<string, T> is generally simpler and more idiomatic than Map<string, T>. Use Map only if you specifically need features like non-string keys, guaranteed insertion-order APIs, or methods such as .set(), .get(), and .has().

